  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ geth version\r\nGeth\r\nVersion: 1.8.6-stable\r\nGit Commit: 12683feca7483f0b0bf425c3c520e2724f69f2aa\r\nArchitecture: amd64\r\nProtocol Versions: [63 62]\r\nNetwork Id: 1\r\nGo Version: go1.10\r\nOperating System: linux\r\nGOPATH=\r\nGOROOT=/usr/lib/go-1.10\r\n```\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\nGeth should not run out of memory\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nOver the course of roughly 24 hours, memory usage by geth increases from ~1GB when run to ~31GB, at which point it's killed by OOMKiller\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\nI'm using the following command:\r\n```geth --syncmode \"full\" --port \"40000\" --rpc  --rpcport \"40001\" --rpcaddr \"0.0.0.0\" --rpccorsdomain \"*\"```\r\n\r\nI'm also querying the RPC server heavily (mostly `eth_getStorageAt` calls)\r\n\r\nI suspect it might have something to do with the heavy RPC usage because everything else should be standard. Maybe something isn't being cleaned up?\r\n\r\n#### Backtrace\r\n\r\nThere is no backtrace\r\n",
